column168: The event occured while loading an MC-331 with Anhydrous Ammonia.  Previously, valves had been opened, sending vapor pressure to the flare.  Due to operator error, the valve to the flare was left open.  A second valve was misaligned allowing liquid to collect in the flare line.     Liquid traveled to the flare and overwelmed the flare, allowing ammonia vapors to be released.    The vapor release was noticed almost immediately by a supervisor.  The valves were identified and the release was stopped in less than 10 minutes.  The total estimated release was 240 gallons.
column169: Procedures are being reviewed and updated.    Ammonia operators are to receive additional training.    A loading checklist is being developed to include a check of valve alingment.

I asked the pro number and I checked it out.  it   was part of the headload on the trailer that had been smashed due to inadequate bracing and blocking.

column168: The drum was punctured by the fork lift operator. The material was cleaned up immediately and left over product was placed in an 85 gallon recovery drum and sent back to the shipper per shippers request.

Upon delivery to another consignee, one of their forklift operators forked the drum. The consignee cleaned up the spilled product and overpacked the damaged drum for safe transit back to the carrier's facility.
column169: The carrier followed up with the other consignee to insure that this issue was handled properly.

column168: Forklift operator was loading palletized goods onto a van trailer that contained drums of referrenced materials.  Forks were protruding slightly beyond the pallet.  upon placing the pallet on the trailer floor, the operator ran the fork into the lower body of the drum, causing a puncture.  The operator was immediately aware of the puncture and laid the drum on its side.  84 pounds of the material were lost from the drum.  Spilled material was contained within the trailer, absorbed, and transferred for disposal as hazardous waste.  Remainder of contents was repackaged into an appropriate container.
column169: Conducted incident investigation and concluded the cause to be operator error.  Operator was provided refresher training.

column168: Dock worker was attempting to load shipment of paint on top of another skid of freight.  He failed to recognize that the bottom pallet was smaller and uneven at the top.  He set the skid of paint on the second pallet and then backed out.  The paint immediately flipped off the bottom pallet.  Result was that the lids on the gallon paint cans in 3 of the boxes popped off and released an approximate total of 3 gallons of paint.  Spill was contained with absorbent compound and cleaned up.  Remainder of shipment was recouped and sent to destination.  Three boxes of paint are being held in haz mat bay for disposition or disposal via environmental contractor.
column169: Dock worker received verbal counseling and written corrective action.  He will also receive remedial forklift training.  Shipment was packaged adequately for transport as received from manufacturer.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: At 1545 hours switch engine YPS-206 reported smell of ammonia at west end of Port of Stockton yard track 2. At 1550 General Manager Dave Buccolo responded to track two and upon investigation observed that top protrective dome cover on car had closure lock pin out and dome cover not secured.  Further investigation when dome cover was lifted found the Pressure reilef valve weeping a small amounbt of product. Valve was disengaged and venting of product stopped. One vapor valve plug was out and one Liquid valve plug was out. These were replaced and tightend and all valves checked and found to be secured properly at 1615.  Car was then taken by switch crew to Consignee Califorina Ammonia Company for inspection and repair of PRV.      This car had vented at West Colton CA on UP on 1/31/06 and UPRR found PRV had enganged and a loose packing gland nut. UPRR repaired car and resealed the protective dome.    It appears this car may have been tampered with enroute to from UPRR West Colton.
column169: Secure Protective dome with cable seal, Shipper should have reported prior problem to consigee so car could be examined and repairs made if needed.

column169: Nail punctures from skids are a huge problem in this industry.  I would like to see plastic skids with indentions for drums to fit in and then band the drum to the skid from the top in an "X" fashion across the top of the drum.  This would prevent up and down movement of the skid in transit.  The carrier can then secure the drums and the skid with straps/ dunnage / 2 x 4's nailed in front and rear and sides, and strap the skid to the trailer wall with applicable strapping.  Wooden skids should be prohibited in the drum industry.  These skids are not made to with stand the weight limitations put upon them.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading product at the consignee location in Clearwater, Florida, a leak occurred.  Apparently, the leak was due to a break in the hose.  Approximately 3 gallons of free product were released to the asphalt surface.  TSE Industries personnel performed the cleanup with the application of quick dry absorbent material to the affected surface.  The spent absorbent material was recovered, and placed into a recovery drum, to be held at the TSE Industries facility, pending disposal per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a faulty hose, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading at the BAX Global facility, a leak was discovered. column168: While loading the product into the tanker at the shipper's location approximately 1.5 pounds of free product was released onto the crash box.  Personnel from the shipper sprayed down the crash box with water to remove the free product and the trailer was released.  While travelling near 49 North Loop East the driver noticed a mist coming from the trailer.  Apparently while the driver was travelling a mist was coming from the area of the crash box that was sprayed down.  The mist affected the tanker and a vehicle that was following behind the tanker.  No soil or waterways were affected.  The Houston Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Bayer Corporation personnel responded to the site and wiped down the tanker.  The tanker was transported to a nearby city yard where final cleanup was performed.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was the result of an error during loading, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: A hazardous materials shipment packaged in non-bulk steel drums was loaded on the transport trailer at Formosa Plastics Corporation on 03/16/2006 and transported by Onyx Environmental Services (OES).    On 03/20/2006 a drum was found to be leaking by an OES employee while the drums were located at the OES in-transit facility in Baytown, Texas and still in route to the destination facility.  The steel drum had become corroded along the sides of the drum at the top.  The contents of the drum were corroding the metal drum from the inside forming a sort of ring at the top where holes eventually formed.  These holes were less than 1/8 of an inch wide.  Liquid material had leaked out of the container, on to the floor of the trailer, and on to the ground.  The drum was immediately placed in a plastic slavage container.  All of the spilled liquids were collected with inorganic absorbent materials.  All contaminated soil and contaminated absorbent materials and any PPE used during the clean up were collected and placed in the same plastic salvage container.  OES employees estimate that approximately 2 gallons (16 pounds) of material was released.
column169: OES has contacted the shipper of the material to inform them of the spill, to determine if the material in the drum was not as described on the shipping manifest, and to see if the drum should have had a liner or have been constructed of another material that would have been compatible with the contents.  The shipper will be informed that future shipments of this material will need to be corrected so that this does not happen again.

column168: The container in question leaked as the result of a puncture caused by a protruding peice of metal located along the floor of the transport vehicle. The container that leaked was one of 27 similar containers and, as the investigation would later reveal, incurred a small puncture when it was loaded into the vehicle. The puncture was at the base of the container and permitted all of the contents to leak out, with only one of the five galons being recovered.     The release lasted approximately an hour or so. Upon discovery, approximately 0ne gallon of the liquid was recovered using spill control supplies available in the vehicle.     The cause of the puncture that lead to the release was identified as a protrucdig piece of metal near the along the floor of the transport vehicle. To eliminate the risk that a similar future incident might occur, the metal protrusion in question was eliminated.
column169: Future similar incidents can be eliminated by carefully inspecting the interior surfaces of the transport vehicles to identify and eliminate any potential hazards, such as the protruding metal. This should elimintae the risk of future container punctures.

column168: Cargo Tank was loaded at railroad site.  Product was transfered from railroad tank car to cargo tank through the cargo tank's cargo hose, product entered cargo tank's vessel through the discharge valve.  After transfer was complete, driver failed to close cargo tank's discharge valve and failed to cap cargo hose.  Driver proceeded to the delivery location.  Upon exiting the I-5 freeway and turning westbound onto California Highway 16, product began spilling from cargo tank.  Driver immediately pulled onto shoulder of roadway, parked and made emergency notification.  Approximately 15 gallons of hydrochloric acid spilled onto roadway.  Police and Fire secured the area and waited for hazardous materials team response.  Valve and cargo hose were secured, environmental response contractor neutrailized spill and recovered material.  Cargo tank and power unit returned to Bulk Transportation terminal for further inspection.  Porduct was delivered the next day to consignee.
column169: Driver was placed into remedial training.  Training program is under further evaluation and possible revision.

Product was steamed to get it to move through hose.
column169: Product needs to deliver at a higher temperature to prevent it from setting up in the hose.

column168: Loader (shipper personnel) loaded cargo tank through the bottom with their equipment and hose. Our driver training engineer was training a new driver.  Loader was to do everything and our driver just had to vent the trailer.  When trailer was loaded, the loader said she wasn't sure how to bleed the pressure off the line so she could disconnect it.  Our training engineer, who was on top of the trailer, offered her some suggestions on disconnecting safely.  When she was having trouble with the disconnect, our new driver took it upon himself to try to help and got sprayed with some product from the pressure in the line. New driver got some product in his ear when he turned his head. He had safety glasses, slicker suit, gloves and hard hat on but didn't have his face shield pulled down.  He was taken to the first aid station where his ear was flushed out.  The ear was still bothering him so he went to the clinic, was checked out and released.
column169: More training in proper disconnect procedures is needed by the plant personnel.  Our new driver that was being trained should not have taken it upon himself to help the loader with the disconnect because he had not had enough training yet himself.

column168: Tanker driver was preparing to unload 1,500 gallons of gasoline to an retail facility's underground storage tank and was unable to properly secure the hose-fitting camlocks to the drop fitting on the fill pipe.  He walked back towards the tanker to adjust the hose to get a better fit and instinctively opened the tanker valve.  The driver realized his error and closed the valve, but gasoline had left the tanker and leaked out of the improperly secured hose fitting.  The release lasted no longer than 2-3 seconds, but approximately 3 gallons of gasoline were released to the concrete surface.  The driver then took spill pads from his truck and cleaned up the spilled product.  No gasoline left facility.  The spill pads were brought back to the terminal and placed in a drum for disposal.
column169: Responsible driver has more than 10 years experience delivering gasoline in tanker trucks and was well trained in proper unloading procedures.  However, he acknowledge that his lack of focus on the task at hand at that time was the cause of this release.  Driver has since been counseled by management to keep focused and ensure that all connections are secure and in order before initiating product flow.  In addition, the driver has been accompanied by a Driver Trainer on subsequent shifts for coaching and evaluation in keeping with Company post-incident policy.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services was on site a customer location top-loading material via the middle dome hatch (trailer is equipped with 3 manways).  At the conclusion of the laoding operation. the driver secured the dome hatch of the manway being used to load the material.  The driver then proceeded to the facility exut when it was discovered that a small amount of material had been released from the rear hatch of the trailer onto the asphlat parking area.  The driver immediately stopped the vehicle, and contained the release.  He then tightened the rear dome hatch and inspected the remaining 2 covers.  The driver, with the assistance of on-site personnel absorbed all material released and containerized for disposal at a licensed disposal facility.  In addition, a field service crew was dispatched to the scne to remove the staining from the facility driveway and to dispose of the containerized debris.
column169: An internal investigation was conducted and it was discovered that the driver did not inspect the rear dome hatch prior as he was preparing to depart the loading facility.  The driver indicated that he had not inspected the rear hatch before departing as he does not normaly use this opening for loading/off-loading operations.  It was also discovered that the trailer had recently been to a tank wash and the rear hatch was not completely secured.  In order to prevent a recirrence, the driver has been re-trained on his reposniblities to ensure the vehicle and load are secured prior to departure.  In addition, formal disciplinary action was taken as a result of his actions that contributed to this release.

column168: OUR CTMV WAS SOUTHBOUND WHEN IT WAS STRUCK HEAD-ON BY A NORTHBOUND VEHICLE DRIVEN BY AN 87 YEAR-OLD WOMAN WHO WE BELIEVE WAS HAVING A HEART ATTACK AND HAD LOST CONSCIOUSNESS.    IMPACT RESULTED IN SEVERE DAMAGE TO STEERING GEAR ON CTMV POWER UNIT.  CTMV TURNED LEFT AND OVERTURNED ONTO CURBSIDE OF TRAILER. (SEE PHONE #1)    CTMV TURNED LEFT AND OVERTURNED ONTO CURBISDE OF TRAILER.  (SEE PHOTO #1)    CTMV SKID ON CURBSIDE APPROX. 100 FT. CAUSING ABRASION HOLES INTANK. (PHOTO #2)    CTMV THEN IMPACTED DITEN BANK CAUSING FRONT BULKHEAD DAMAGE. (PHOTO #3)    CTMV ROLLED OVER ONTO DRIVE SIDE AND CAME TO REST.    MY COMPANY HAD A REPRESENTATIVE ON SCENE WITHIN 40 MINUTES AND WAS ABLE TO PLUG ALL THE LEAKS.  HOWEVER A SIZABLE QUANTITY HAD BEEN LOST PRIOR TO THE POINT.  OUR COMPANY ARRIVE AT 1:10 PM WITH PUMP TRUCK AND A 2ND EMPTY CTMV AND EQUIPMENT NECESSARY TO DRILL AND PUMP-OUT OVERTURNED CTMV.    AT 5:00 PM THE YATES COUNTY EMERGENCY COORDINATOR GAVE US THE GREEN LIGHT TO BEGIN PUMPING OPERATIONS. (PHOTO #4)    PUMP OUT CONCLUDED AT 7:00 PM WITH THE RECOVERY OF 6,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE OUT OF A $9,200 GALLON LOAD. (3,200 GALLONS SPILLED)

column168: THE RAIL CAR, CNA 385394 WAS LOADED WITH AMMONIUM NITRATE AT AN RESOURCES BRANDON, MB PLANT.  WHEN IT ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE, WAMPUM HARDWARE, NEW CASTLE, PA IT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING IN THE "B" END SLIDE GATE AREA.  UPON INVESTIGATION, A BUILD UP OF AMMONIUM NITRATE RESIDUE ON THE RAIL CAR FRAME WAS FOUND INDICATING LEAKAGE HAD OCCURRED FOR SOME PART OF THE TRIP.  A ROLLING RAIL CAR WEIGHT WAS TAKEN BY THE CN RR IN WINNIPEG INDICATING THAT THE CAR HAD DEVELOPED A SLIGHT LEAK IN THE EARLY PART OF THE TRIP.  IMMEDIATELY AN RESOURCES ORDERED THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN, THE DELIVERY RAILROAD, TO HAVE THEIR RAILROAD SECURITY POLICE TO INVESTIGATE THE RAIL CAR CONDITION AND VERIFY THE RAIL CAR SLIDE GATES AND LIDS HAD NOT BEEN BREACHED.  AN RESOURCES ALSO ORDERED THE NORFOLK SOUTHERN TO TAKE THE CAR TO THEIR NEAREST CERTIFIED SCALE AND PROVIDE A WEIGHT TO DETERMINE THE AMOUNT OF AMMONIUM NITRATE LOST EN ROUTE.  THIS LOSS AMOUNT IS RECORDED IN # 19 ON PAGE 1.
column169: AT THIS TIME THE RAIL CAR WILL BE INSPECTED WHEN IT RETURNS TO AN RESOURCES IN BRANDON, MB.  IF STRUCTURAL DEFECTS ARE SUSPECTED TO HAVE CAUSED THE LEAK, THE RAIL CAR WILL BE RETURNED TO THE MANUFACTURER FOR REPAIRS.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  Upon arrival of the tanker at the consignee's location a small leak was discovered coming from the tanker.  Approximately one teaspoon of free product was released and affected some asphalt.  Apparently the release was due to a crack in the shell liner of the tanker.  Exxon Mobil personnel applied absorbents to the affected asphalt area and placed a bucket underneath the leaking area of the tanker to contain the free liquid.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. dispatched a new tanker to the scene for product transfer.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was related to a crack in the shell liner of the tanker, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: INTERNATIONAL SHIPMENT WAS MISSING INFORMATION ON EXPORT DOCUMENTS. SHIPMENT INSPECTED DUE TO MISSING INFORMATION. INSPECTION REVEALED INNER PLASTIC BAG THAT WAS MARKED "DRY ICE". INSPECTION OF THE BAG REVEALED IT CONTAINED A SINGLE OBJECT THAT APPEARED TO BE DRY ICE (MAINTAINED TEMPERATURE WELL BELOW 32F, GAVE OFF GAS VAPOR, BAG AND PACKAGE WERE NOT COLLECTING CONDENSED WATER.) NO INDICATION IN THE EXPORT PAPERWORK OR ON THE PACKAGE THAT THE CONTENTS INCLUDED DRY ICE OR WERE REFRIGERATED. THE OUTER CARTON IS MARKED ONLY WITH THE UPS STORE AND THE UPS EMBLEM (PRE PRINTED).

THE TRAILER CONTAINING THE SHIPMENT WAS BROUGHT UP TO THE DOCK DOOR TO BE UNLOCKED.  WHEN THE DOCKWORKER OPENED THE DOOR TO THE TRAILER AND LOOKED INSIDE HE NOTICED MOISTURE ALONG THE SIDE OF THE PALLET ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DOCKWORKER WENT AND GOT THE SUPERVISOR.  WE APPLIED ABSORBENT TO THE TRAILER FLOOR TO ABSORB THE SPILL AND UNWRAPPED THE PACKAGE CONTAINING 4 DRUMS OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL AND FOUND THAT 1 DRUM WAS LEAKING FROM THE SEAM OF THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  WE PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM ON INSIDE OF WORKER PALLET CARRYING CARDBOARD AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL.
column169: WE PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM WITH A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED IT TO THE SHIPPER FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  WE ALSO SUGGESTED THAT A LARGER PALLET BE USED.  4 DRUMS HAD BEEN PLACED ON 1 PALLET AND WRAPPED TOGETHER. THE DRUMS HUNG OVER THE PALLET ON ALL FOUR SIDES WHICH MAY CAUSE SOME UNDO PRESSURE ON THE SEAM DUNNAGE CAUSING IT TO LEAK.

On 3/22 shipper attempted to ship a NDA pkg marked and labeled as isopropanol,   UN1219, with Class 3 hazard label. Oakland Center driver Jaques Rickman refused the pcg as shipper was not a hazmat contract shipper and it did not have hazmat shipping papers. Rickman states that customer asked if he would take the pkg if they covered the hazmat marking and labels; he refused to do so. On 3/23 Rickman was suspicious of the pkgs offered by shipper and asked for them to be checked when he returned to the center.  Pkgs had no hazmat marking or labels of any kind but were found to contain isopropanol.  1zat27360151401083: shipper overpacked the marked and labeled pkg that Rickman refused the day before; pkg contains 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottle, "70% lsopropyl Rubbing Alcohol”.  1zat27360149507474: pkg contains 3 fiberboard Inner cartons: 1 x 1 gallon plastic bottle “70% lsopropyl Rubbing Alcohol”; 4 x 16 oz. plastic bottle, “Brush Off Makeup Brush Cleanser” marked flammable; 5 boxes “EcoSoft” tissue; 4 x 250 ml plastic bottle “My Pillow” makeup remover; 37pcs various cosmetics.

column168: INCIDENT HAPPENED WHILE LOADING A DELIVERY TRAILER SKID OF 4 DRUMS ALREADY LOADED.  ASSOCIATE WAS WORKING A SKID OF OTHER FREIGHT NEXT TO THE SKID OF DRUMS.  THE ASSOCIATE WAS NOT AWARE THAT THERE WAS A BROKEN BOARD STICKING OUT FROM THE SKID HE WAS LOADING.  AS HE WAS MOVING THE SKID IN NEXT TO THE DRUMS, THE BROKEN BOARD PUNCTURED THE 55 GALLON DRUM APPROX 3 INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE PUNCTURE WAS APPROX 15 INCHES IN DIAMETER.  THE ASSOCIATE QUICKLY LIFTED THE SKID OF DRUMS WITH THE FORKLIFT AND PUT A 55 GAL PLASTIC TRASH CAN UNDER IT TO CAPTURE THE SPILL.  APPROX 50 GALLONS OF PAINT RUN INTO THE TRASH CAN.  APPROX 1-2 GALLONS SPILLED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THIS WAS CONTAINED WITH OIL DRY AND PLACED INTO THE TRASH CAN WITH THE SPILLED PAINT.  THE TRASH CAN OF SPILLED PAINT WAS LIFTED & PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM & SEALED.  START TO FINISH, THE PAINT WAS CONTAINED IN APPROX 15 MINUTES, INCLUDING THE CLEANUP.
column169: ASSOCIATE HAD BEEN COUNSELED & TRAINED REGARDING THE INCIDENT.  ASSOCIATE MUST INSPECT FREIGHT PRIOR TO LOADING TO INSURE SAFE & INCIDENT FREE LOADING.  THE BROKEN BOARD ON THE PALLET SHOULD HAVE BEEN NOTICED AND REMOVED PRIOR TO LOADING INTO THE TRAILER.  THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS A TRAINING TOPIC TO CREATE AWARENESS OF COMPROMISING SITUATIONS CAN CAUSE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INCIDENTS & POTENTIAL DANGERS.

ON MARCH 10, 2006 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 PM A LOADER PLACED AN IBC OF WASTE CAUSTIC CLEANER INSIDE DUPRE TRANPSORTATION TRAILER #CC63069.  HE PROCEEDED TO LOAD OTHER MATRIALS ONTO THE TRAILER WHEN HE WAS NOTIFIED BY ANOTHER EMPLOYEE THERE WAS LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE NIGHT SHIFT SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND THE CLEAN-UP CREW IMMEDIATELY BEGAN OFFLOADING THE TRAILER.  THE IBC WAS POSITIONED SO THAT LIQUID NO LONGER LEAKED OUT.  WE ESTIMATE 40 GALLONS WAS LOST FROM THE IBC, BUT WAS CONTIANED IN A CONCRETE AREA BENEATH THE TRAILER.  THE LIQUID REMAINING IN THE LEAKING IBC WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER IBC.  ALL MATERIAL WHICH LEAKED OUT OF THE TRAILER ALONG WITH THE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER WAS SOLIDIFIED WITH ABSORBANT AND PLACED INTO 2-55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN SENT TO SERVICE TRANSPORT TO BE FURTHER CLEANED AMD DECONTAMINATED.  THERE WERE NONINJURIES, NO PROPERTY DAMAGE AND 100% OF THE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED.
column169: WILL RECOMMEND IMPLEMENTATION OF REGIONAL POLICY TO DISCONTINUE USE OF THIS TYPE OF IBC FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS UNLESS THE IBC IS NEW.

column168: This shipment was found to be leaking in the FedEx warehouse. Upon inspection of the contents during spill cleanup the inner container was found to be on it’s side although it contained a liquid. The Material Safety Data Sheet was obtained and the flash point is listed as -4 degrees F and as Printing Ink, 3, UN 1210. As the shipper did not offer the package with any DG markings, DG labels, nor with a Shippers Declaration it is believed to be an undeclared dangerous goods. 1t’s also believed to be a hidden package discrepancy as the inner container was not right side up containing a liquid. FAA agent David Hendricks was notified on 3/23/06 at apr. 10:20 a.m. Central time. FedEx held the shipment at the location pending FAA investigation.

column168: Trailer was loaded with spent sulfuric acid enroute to unload location.  Bolts on unloading line, top of trailer, were loose at bottom flange.  Approximately 1.5 miles before unload location, product leaked into crash box area then went through drain tubes onto ground.  When driver arrived at unload location, he tightened flange and unloaded trailer.  ERS of Ohio, Inc. was called to scene to perform clean-up.  Product was neutralized with soda ash then removed and properly disposed by ERS.  Trailer was rinsed off at unload site before returning to K-Limited terminal.
column169: K-Limited has three trailers in this application hauling spent and fresh sulfuric acid.  We have implemented a weekly maintenance program to be performed by the K-Limited maintenance department.  A checklist has been developed to give a step by step procedure for performing preventative maintenance and safety check by the shop personell.  Also, only most qualified K-Limited drivers are trained in this application.  New training is also being performed to instruct drivers proper safety checks before each trip.  These steps are now standard operating procedures.  K-Limited has performed this daily multi-load, averages 4 to 6 rounds per day, since 1997 with no maintenance incident of this type.  We feel these new corrective actions will prevent this type of incident from ever happenning again.

SunPro found one (55 gallon drum) HazMat (FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, NOS (1,2,4-TRIMETHYLBENZENE, PETROLEUM NAPTHA) CLASS 3 UN 1993, PG III) leaking and approx 10 gallons released. Five drums were heavily damaged but, no leak. Leaking drum was plugged and placed in overpack. Five damaged drums were also placed into overpacks. These six overpacked drums would not fit back into the rail container therefore the shipper requested SunPro deliver six drum directly to them on 3/20/2006. Rail container also delivered 3/20/2006. column168: THE 55 GAL ARRIVED IN LONG BEACH CWX FACILITY AT ABOUT 5:45 AM FROM OUR FACILITY IN SANTA FE SPRINGS. THE TRAILER WAS BROKE OUT BY EMPLOYEE ALEX MEJIR WHO AT THE TIME NOTICE DAMAGE TO THE DRUM BUT DID NOT SEE IT LEAKING. THE DRUM WAS THEN PUT IN FRONT OF THE LOADING DOOR FOR THE ROUTE DRIVER TO TAKE LATER ON . AT ABOUT 10:30 AM IT WAS TIME TO PUT THE DRUM INSIDE THE ROUTE TRAILOR WHEN IT WAS NOTICABLE THAT THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS ALREADY HAD A CREASE ON THE MIDDLE OF THE DRUM. IT WAS ALREADY LEAKING WHEN THE PRODUCT WAS GOING TO BE MOVED AGAIN. THE LIQUID WAS SMALL QUANTITY AND NOT MUCH CAME OUT. I WENT AHEAD AND TURN THE BARREL TO IT'S SIDE SO NO MORE CAME OUT. THE DRUM WAS SECURED PROPERLY SO THAT THE CONTENT WOULD NOT LEAK FURTHER MORE.
column169: AS A TRUCKING COMAPNY , CWX HAS PUT IN PLACE MANY RESOURCES IN DEALING WITH INCIDENT LIKE THE ONE WE HAVE HERE. WE MUST BE SURE TO LOAD THERE SHIPMENTS WITH ENOUGH PROTECTION SO THAT WHEN THEY ARE IN TRANSIT THEY DON'T GET DAMAGED OR PUNCTURED. AS A UNLOADER, WE MUST BE SURE TO BE CAREFUL AND RECOGNIZE SUCH RISK. PROPER METHODS OF UNLOADING AND USAGE OF FORKLIFT MUST BE USED TO ENSURE THE SAFETY OF THESE PRODUCTS.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: This particular incident involved a heavy duty forklift battery that was fairly large in size. It was on a pallet staged in a trailer that was being unloaded. When the forklift operator picked up the pallet with the battery on it the pallet broke causing the battery to slide backward and subsequently to tip over. About two gallons of the battery acid spilled out of the caps before the battery could be uprighted. Spilled material was neutralized and the battery was placed on a new and stronger pallet.
column169: Shippers need to choose and select proper size and constructed pallets that can support their shipments.

column168: 3/15/06: A shipment arrived at the Seaboard Marine, Ltd. (SML) CFS facility via motor vehicle with freight container/chassis attached (non-SML truck/driver). Upon the opening of subject unit, it was observed that there was a white powder substance on the unit floor just beneath one of the pallets of cargo. At that time, SML loading personnel informed the driver of the situation and asked that he contact his management.     While waiting for a response from the shipper, SML management made the decision to call an environmental response contractor to perform remediation of the spill. The contractor, SWS, arrived within the hour and transferred the source of the spill (one damaged bag) into a salvage drum. Once the drum was sealed and labeled, SWS departed the scene and stated that the salvage drum would be picked up the following day. The shipping papers were corrected to reflect the removed package by the shipper and faxed to our personnel for shipment.    3/16/06: Salvage drum was picked up by SWS and delivered back to their facility for proper disposal.    END OF REPORT

column168: ON THE MORNING OF 03/23/2006 EMPLOYEE EVERETT STURGEON CALLED ME OVER TO INSPECT A CHEMICAL SPILL.  I IMMEDIATELY WENT OVER TO WHERE THE SPILL WAS AND OBSERVED A PERFECTLY INTACT SKID WITH A PIECE OF PLYWOOD ON IT. column168: Received a call from Univar driver at approximately 7:30 AM. Driver advised he had 8 drums of sodium hypochlorite 12.5% on his trailer of which at least one was leaking. He was parked near the rear of the Flying-J Truck Stop in Orange, TX when he noticed the liquid leaking from the trailer. He was parked in an area which contained the leaking liquid. Univar response team arrived at the scene at approximately 9:30 AM. The leaking drum was placed into a recovery drum. Estimated amount of material spilled was 5 gallons. Spilled material in the trailer and the concrete was neutralized with citric a then swept up and placed into the recovery drum. Decision was made to contact Hulcher Professional Services hazardous material response team to assist with the clean-up. Hulcher and Univar personnel applied floor-dry to the floor of the trailer and the concrete area, swept up and placed into a 55 gallon 0/H drum. The trailer was sent to Service Transport to complete the clean-up process. The spilled, and clean-up materials were disposed of through Univar’s waste disposal service.

GATX 18597 observed leaking from bottom outlet valve upon arrival at CN Memphis Yard, Memphis, TN on Train M31971-28. Car was isolated on the Southend of Track MA-13. CN HazMat Response Team arrived on scene and did inspection that revealed bottom outlet valve was a top-operated bottom outlet. They removed shipper seal IMTT 0898 from the stuffing box cap and were able to close the valve stopping the leak. They also tightened the packing gland nut on the valve stem. The stuffing box was re-sealed with seal ICGRR ZH 70273. They then checked the bottom outlet cap and found it to be only hand tight. They removed the cap and checked gasket then replaced cap and made tool tight. Car was okayed to go to destination at approximately 0800 hours.

column168: At approximately 1248 hours on March 23,2006, a loading operator was loading acetone from the plant storage tank to a tank car.  The loading platform where the tank car was being loaded is inside a concrete containment system.  The tank car developed a leak while loading on the belly side of the tank.  Acetone and phenol was captured in the containment system.  This tank car had phenol as a prior load and was cleaned by a third party facility before the loading operator loaded the truck with acetone.
column169: First Class Services will be performing an inspection on this tank car to find root cause of leak.  First Class indicated they would have the report available within the next 2-3 weeks.

column168: NATX 29053, Residue Last Contained Alcohols, N.O.S., was discovered to be dripping product from the bottom outlet valve in CSX Transportation’s rail yard in Selkirk, NY. The car was isolated and the shipper, Aventine Renewable Energy, Inc was notified via CHEMTREC (report # 03042006031). CSXT’s hazardous materials department responded an emergency response contractor, Miller Environmental, to repair the source of the leak. Miller tightened the bottom outlet valve extension pipe cap and the leak stopped. It is estimated about 1 quart of product was released. The car was then released to continue to destination.        CAUSE CODE: 662 (Bottom Outlet cap loose)  NARRI: 5(4+3+0) x (2+0) = 70

column168: On Friday, March 17, 2006 at approximately 1120 hours, a truck driver was unloading Sulfuric Acid (66° Grade) from the cargo tank motor vehicle (CTMV) to a plant storage tank, V-61 1. The storage tank is located inside a plastic containment dike.  The driver was working with a GE representative to service test a recently installed high level detection device. The tank was filled to a higher than normal level in order to complete the test. Once it was recognized that the detection device was not operational, the transfer was secured leaving about 50 gallons of freeboard area in the 550-gallon tank.  To complete the transfer process, the driver cleared the unloading hose through the loading line and into the tank. Air from this process caused the acid to start splashing around within the tank. The splashing caused approximately 10 gallons of material to flow out of a cracked-open manway into the secondary containment with a small portion spraying beyond the containment to a nearby concrete wall.  The driver immediately stopped the line clearing process while he and a GE representative began washing down material that had sprayed onto the wall. An internal spill report was completed and the incident was reported to management.  There were no injuries or personnel exposures resulting from this release. Neither the tank truck nor the GE Storage tank failed.
column169: The cause of the release was related to the following: 1. ) Manway loose on top of tank, 2. Failure of recently installed high-level detection device, and 3.) Filling tank beyond desirable safe limit. Corrective actions include: 1.) Secure the manway on the storage tank sine a 4" atmospeheric vent is already installed on the tank, as well as evaluating if there are other storage tanks with a similar problem, 2.) Investigate and correct the failure mode of the high-level detection device, and 3.) Properly note max fill limit on storage tank sight glass.

column168: BNSF mechanical carman working in the railyard reported propane odor emanting from the adjacent track that the carman was inspecting. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was immediately dispatched to this area and began investigating odor source. lnvstigation revealed entrained PLMX 137566 as the odor source. PLMX 137566 was found with the liquid valve’s 2 inch closure plug not applied; and the valve’s wheeled valve handle loose and not fully closed. Responder closed the valve and tightened the wheeled valve handle stem nut. The closure plug threads were cleaned by the responder, inserted into its orifice and tool tightened. After this securement was completed no further product odor was evident. Responder also checked the securement of all other valves and fittings on PLMX 137566, finding no other securement exceptions.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the mechanical fitness and securement of all valves and fittings.

Driver failed to properly relieve the pressure on the line after transferring product from cargo tank to customer's storage tank.  When he went to disconnect the hose, some product splashed in his eyes, on his face and clothes. He was immediately taken to the emergency shower and eye wash to be rinsed for 15 minutes.  He was then taken to the clinic where he was examined and released back to work.  Driver was not wearing the prescribed PPE.
column169: Driver failed to follow standard procedure as trained annually, by relieving the pressure in the line prior to disconnecting the hose.  He also was not wearing the required PPE, as trained annually.  Both concerns will be highlighted in our annual training in June.

column25: G. E. PLASTICS MT. VERNON, INC.
column168: On 3/20/06 at approximately 1000 hrs a First Class Services, Inc. truck and tank trailer had left G.E. Mt. Vernon loaded with Phenol. The driver stopped just outside the G.E. plant to inspect his truck and trailer. The driver noticed the tank leaking a very small amount of product which did not make contact with the ground. The leak was patched and the product was returned to G.E. Mt. Vernon. After a investigation of the incident, it was determined that during a wash—out, following a previous load, a large amount of pressure and heat was applied to the tank which shocked the tank and caused rapid expansion. The shock and rapid expansion of the tank resulted in a fracture of the tank.
column169: Commercial wash out procedures have been evaluated and changed to eliminate a reoccurrence of this incident.

column168: 3/8/06; At approximately 12:15pm, CR Risk Mgmt. A. Richter notified by CR Assistant Superintendent R. Gloede, that tank carUTLX 201823, load Methanol, 3, UN 1230, PG II, was reported leaking from the top of the car, while located on Track #3 in the East End of the Departure Yard at Oak Island Yard, Newark, NJ. Emergency response contractor REACT was at the yard performing scheduled work, and was notified. Inspection performed by REACT’s R. Gould, and CR Mechanical Mgr. R. Rose. An intact seal was removed from the tank car’s breadbox. Messrs. Gould and Rose found the 3” liquid valve (new), threaded onto the base, was extremely loose and could be turned by 2 fingers. Car’s internal pressure relieved through 1” air valve, immediately stopping leak. The liquid valve was removed, thread dope applied to threads, and valve reapplied tool tight. Car secured and okayed for Actual preparer of the tank car for shipment was IMTT, Bayonne, NJ, for account of Ashland Chemical, Columbus, OH. Car being forwarded to originally assigned destination, Pfizer, Kalamazoo, Ml.

The bobtail was backing out of a private residence when the rear brakes failed.  To avoid backing through two lanes of oncoming traffic, our driver put the bobtail into the homeowner's ditch next to the driveway where a tree stopped the truck.  In doing this emergency stop the piping that connects to the hose reel was cracked releasing a small amount of vapor for approximately two minutes.  In investigating the brake system on the bobtail it was found that the lining of the brakes was down to the rivets of the brake shoes.  Our truck had just had it's 5000 mile inspection 16 days prior on March 14, 2006 and Ferrrellgas was advised the lining was at 30%.
column169: Ferrellgas is no longer doing business with this inspection company and we have taken our business elsewhere.

column168: Notification was received at the corporate office that tank car ACFX 18653 was leaking while en route to our FL facility from Enid, OK.  Driver was dispatched to investigate the leak and found that liquid was weeping from the safety relief valve.    Driver commenced offloading material from the tank car, and the safety relief valve reseated and ceased leaking.  After approximately an hour of offloading material, the driver checked the dome area for leaks with litmus paper and found none.  Tank car was moved to our facility for further offloading and repair.      Initial investigation into the cause of the leak seems to indicate that the tank car may have been overfilled, and expansion of the liquid due to temperature may have caused the relief valve to lift.  After the tank car was emptied and degassed, a mobile repair crew removed the safety valve to determine if there was any contributing damage.  None was found, so the valve was reinstalled and its o-rings replaced.  Corrective actions are being pursued with the supplier at this time.    Less than 50 pounds of material was estimated to have been released.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.
column169: Corrective action is currently being pursued with the supplier.

column168: APPROXIMATELY 48 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS SPILLED DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE PRODUCT AT THE PREVIOUSLY IDENTIFIED CONSIGNEE FACILITY. THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN THE CARRIERS PRODUCT HOSE SEPARATED ROM ITS COUPLING AT THE CUSTOMERS END OF THE HOSE.THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS AAPPROXIMATELY 30 SECONDS. DRIVER CLOSED THE TRAILERS INTERNAL VALVE AND SHUTDOWN PUMP ON TRACTOR. FACILITY PERSONNEL USED SORBENT PADS SAVAGE BOOM AND FLOORDAY MATERIAL TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE DISCHARGED PRODUCT MIGRATED ACROSS 100 OF CONCRETE PARKING LOT INTO A CONCRETER STORM DETENTION AQUEDUCT. ALL DISCHARED PRODUCT WAS CONATINED AND CLEAN UP ON THE CUSTOMER PROPERTY. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED WHEN THE TRANSPORT DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO PUMP OFF FUEL INTO A CUSTOMERS ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. THE TANKS OVERALL PROCTECTION VALVE WAS  JAMMED IN THE CLOSED POSITION PREVENTING THE PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE TANK. IT CAUSING SEVERE BACK FLOOR PRESSURE ON THE PRODUCT HOSE AND PUMP. BECAUSE THERE WAS TOO MUCH PRESSURE FOR THE PUMPS PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE TO HANDLE. THE PRODUCT HOSE BLEW OFF ITS COUPLING APPARENTLY ON THE PREVIOUS DELIVERY THE TANK HAD BEEN FILLED TO CAPACITY GREATER THAN 90 CAUSING ITS OVER FILL PROTECTION VALVE TO CLOSE AND REMAIN JAMMED. SPECIFICALLY THE DRIVER WHO MADE THE PREVIOUS DELIVERY CONTINUED TO FILL THE TANK 11 MINUTES AFTER OVERFILL PROTECTION VALVE CLOSED AT 901 OF THE TANKS CAPACITY. THE EXTRA PRODUCT ENTERED THE TANK THROUGH ITS OVERFILL BYPASS SYSTEM. NO SPILL OCURED. THE DRIVER STATES THAT HE DID NOT REALIZE THE VALVE HAD CLOSED AT 901 OF THE TANKS CAPACITY, BECAUSE NO ALARM SOUNDED AT THE THE RACK.
column169: CORRECTIVE/ PREVENTIVE ACTIONS:    1 A NEW OVERFILL PROTECTION BALL VLVE HAS BEEN INSTALLED ON STORAGE TANKS  2 THE CARRIERS TRACTOR PUMP IS BEING EVALUATED TO ENSURE ITS OPERBILITY INCLUDING ITS PRV  3 A REPRESENTATIVE OF CONSIGNEE WILL BE ON SCENE TO MONITOR ALL FUTURE DELIVERES.    4 THE CONSIGNEE WILL ENSURE THAT THE AUDIBLE ALARM ON THE STORAGE TANK'S OVER FILL PROTECTION SYSTEM CAN BE HEARD BY THE DRIVER, WHO DELIVERED PRODUCT.  5 A COPY OF THE APPLICABLE STORGAE TANK STOPPING CHARTS WILL BE MADE AVAILABLE TO THE DRIVER

column168: During a routine BNSF outbound train inspection in the railyard, the mechanical inspector reported GATX 44013 dripping liquid from the top of the tank car and down its’ side shell. The BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder investigating the leak source reported a 4-5 inch wide stain on the side shell of GATX 44013. Responder also reported finding the top operated bottom outlet valve’s (TOBOV) operating rod loose. The TOBOV operating rod was rotated to close 1/2 turn and packing nut tightened. Liquid appeared to have been escaping from around the orifice base of the operating rod. The packing material was not checked. After the responder completed the initial securement of the TOBOV, GATX 44013 was isolated in the railyard for continued observation. On 3/23/06, GATX 44013 was switched in the railyard and no further leakage was detected. All previous spillage evaporated, including any ballast/ground impact drips. On 3/29/06, GATX 44013 was observed in St. Louis, MO with similar problems. Liquid was leaking from the manway cover and the TOBOV top operating rod area. It was determined at this time that GATX 44013 was overfilled. The shipper reduced the lading in GATX 44013 by 2000 gallons on 3/31/06.
column169: Ensure shipper’s pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings. Also, shipper should validate current outage tables and adhere to the proper levels for the transported commodity in the transport package.

column168: NEWPORT NEWS SHIPBUILDING (NNS) IS IN THE INITIAL PHASES OF OVERHAULING THE AIRCRAFT CARRIER, U.S.S. VINSON AT OUR FACILITY LOCATED IN NEW PORT NEWS, VIRGINIA.  NNS PERSONNEL REMOVED TWO CHEMICAL DETECTION UNITS ON MARCH 29, 2006, AND TURNED THE UNITS OVER TO AMSEC, LLC, WHO IS PROVIDING STORAGE AND WAREHOUSING SERVICES FOR THE 3-YEAR OVERHAUL.    THE CHEMICAL DETECTION UNITS ARE SIMILAR IN SIZE AND CONTIAN AN EQUIVALIENT QUANTITY OF AMERCIUM 241-AS A HOME SMOKE DETECTOR.  EACH UNIT CONTAINS 0.0002 CURIES OF AMERICIUM 241.  THE UNITS WERE TAGGED AMSEC PERSONNEL WITH A COMPET-GENERATED INVENTORY CONTROL SHEET DOCUMENTING THE MATERIAL TRANSFER AND FUTURE STORAGE LOCATION.  AMSEC SHIPPED THE UNITS ON INTERSTATE 664 TO THE CARRIER OUTFITTING MATERIAL SUPPORT CENTER LOCATED 6 MILES SOUTH OF NNS IN SUFFOLK, VIRGINIA.    THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO EITHER CASING AND THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF AMERCIUM 241 TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR EXPOSURE TO SHIPPING PERSONNEL.  NNS IS REPORTING THIS SHIPMENT TO THE DOT AS AN "UNDECLARED HAZMAT SHIPMENT" BECASUE THE UNITS WERE SHIPPED WITHOUT AN OUTER CONTAINER AND THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED WITH THE UN ID NUMBER AS REQUIRED.    THE UNITS WERE SHIPPED WITHOUT EXERNAL PACKAGING; HOWEVER, THE EXCEPTED QUANTITY OF AMERCIUM 241 WAS CONTAINED AND SEALED WITHIN THE DECTECTOR UNITS PROTECTIVE CASING.  THE UNITS DID NOT CONTIAN THE UN ID NUMBER FO RTHE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED QUANTITY FOR INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES PER 49 CFT PART 173.421.  HOWEVER, THE UNITS ARE MARKED WITH THE RADIOACTIVE "TREFOIL" SYMBOL ON THE EXTERNAL CASING.
column169: ONCE THE DISCREPANCY WAS DISCOVERED, NNS DIRECTED AMSEC TO SHIP THE CHEMICAL DETECTOR UNITS BACK TO THE U.S.S. VINSON WITH THE FOLLOWING INSTRUCTIONS:    1.  PLACE THE DETECTORS IN A POLY BAG AND SEAL CLOSED.    2.  MARK THE POLY BAG AS "RADIOACTIIVE".    3.  PLACE THE DETECTORS IN A BOX MEETING THE REQUIREMENTS OF 49 CFR PART 173.410.    4.  SEAL THE BOX.    5.  MARK THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX WITH "UN2911".  THIS IS THE DESIGNATED UN ID NUMBER        FOR "RADIOACTIVE" MATERIAL, EXCEPTED QUANTITY, INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES."    6.  THE UNITS WERE SHIPPED BACK USING NNS' "MATERIAL TRANSFER" SHIPPING DOCUMENT.    PRESENTLY OUR CORRECTIVE ACTIONS INCLUDE:    1.  RE-TRAINED NNS SHIPPING PERSONNEL TO RECOGNIZE EXCEPTED QUANTITIES OF         READIOACTIVE MATERIAL.    2.  EMPHASIZED MARKING AND PACKAGINGING REQUIREMENTS FOR EXCEPTED QUANTITIES OF         RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL.    3.  MEETING WITH AMSEC PERSONNEL AND PROVIDE GUIDANCE REGARDING THE PACKAGINING,         MARKING AND SHIPPING OF EXCEPTED QUANTITIES OF RADIOACITVE MATERIAL.

column168: Our driver was proceeding East on St. Rt. 122, approximately 1/2 mile west of St. Rt. 42, near Waynesville, OH. Roadway is a two-lane highway, with one lane for each direction of vehicular travel. It was dark and raining. Our driver perceived that a vehicle, later described as a pick-up truck, was over the centerline of the highway coming toward our vehicle in our lane of traffic. Our drive attempted to slow down and pulled to the right side of roadway onto berm area which was basically lined by a ditch line with adjacent field. Our unit traveled partially into the ditch line and our driver corrected and pulled back onto highway and then again onto the right berm a:rea; noticing that the trailer portion of our tractor trailer combination was being jostled around behind him. Just as driver came to rest on the right berm area, along the grassy area adjacent to the ditch line the wet ground gave way, into the ditch, and the vehicle rolled over onto its right side. Our Company personnel responded, as did the Ohio State Highway Patrol and the loca[ Cleeicreek Fire Department. The Ohio State Highway Patrol closed St. Ri. 122, at points adjacent to the accident scene in order to provide a safe area to remediate the accident situation. Our remedial activity consisted of our personnel responding to site, determining status of equipment and commodity being transported. it was noted there was no evidence of product spillage; but the unit was resting on the right loading/off- loading side of the trailer and that we would have to manually create an opening in trai][er barrel in order to evacuate the product from the vessel. After securing area, our personnel proceeded with drilling holes into the side barrel of tank trailer; inserted hose into said openings and used the product pump from a second transport unit that we had dispatched to the scene. The product was pumped out of the wrecked unit onto the additional unit we had brought onto the scene. The services of a wrecker company were utilized to upright our “wrecked” vehicle and to then transport the tractor-trailer units to respective repair facilities. The entire process was overseen and observed by the personnel from the Ohio State Highway, Patrol and the noted fire departments and all parties were satisfied that no product spillage, of any kind, had occurred either as a result of the accident or from the off-loading and removal of the unit from the accident scene. The trailer and all operating components retained structural integrity throughout the incident with no escape of product onto or into the area. As there was no release of product there was no environmental remediation required or performed as a result of this incident.

column168: A Car inspector was inspecting 46 cars on # 5 South Yard track in Kirk Yard. He walked along the south side of the track, first, performing the inspection then proceeded to walk along the north side of the track to complete the inspection. As he past by two tank cars he got a breath of fumes. He completed his inspection of the track. Removed his Blue Flag Protection. Drove back to the cars, recorded the identification numbers, and returned to the West End Tower office. Upon notification of the incident, the employee was taken to USS dispensary for precautionary evaluation, the Transportation department was advised of car emitting fumes and the area was evacuated. The Transportation department identified the product, notified the car shipper of the incident, and first responders were contacted to inspect the car.
column169: Procedures followed to the letter; Employee reported incident, Employee taken for medical evaluation, Area was evacuated, Shipper notified, First responders notified, Car secured and product contained by first responders.  Investigation Team:  Ron Couch - Transportation  Gerry Carr - Transportation  Dale Knapp — Mechanical  Dan Studer — Mechanical  Other comments:  Employee medical evaluation indicated no ill effects from exposure to fumes.  Tank car GATX 300695 has defective valve packing in bottom drain valve.  First responder SUNPRO secured car and provided containment protection.  Car was moved to Track 10 D&R for load transfer.  SUNPRO has arranged for railcar to be shipped to sight for transferring load.  Transfer is scheduled for 3-13-06 and will be managed by SUNPRO

THE TOBOV OPERATING ROD WAS ROTATED TO CLOSURE AND PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC) SUBSTANTIALLY EBBED. THE BOC WAS PRODUCT DAMP AND APPEARED TOOL TIGHT. THE BOC GASKET WAS NOT INSPECTED. ACFX 76845 WAS MOVED TO THE CONTAINMENT PIT FOR FURTHER OBSERVATION. THE NEXT DAY, AS NO FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE WAS EVIDENT FROM THE BOC, ACFX 76845 WAS RELEASED TO PROCEED TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: CMC RR SWITCH CREW REPORTED TO THE BNSF TRAINMASTER THAT NATX 300257 (WHICH RECENTLY ARRIVED DAYTON RAILYARD) WAS DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM VALVE (BOV) AREA. BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FOUND PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET ASSEMBLY. THE TWO INCH CLOSURE PLUG ON THE BOV WAS IMMEDIATELY TOOL TIGHTENED AND DRIPPING CEASED. THE BOTTOM OPERATED BOV HANDLE WAS MANEUVERED TO ENSURE THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS PROPERLY CLOSING. AN ATTEMPT WAS MADE TO REMOVE THIS PLUG TO CHECK THE THREADED CONNECTION, BUT WHEN THE PLUG WAS LOOSENED, PRODUCT SEEPED FROM AROUND THE PLUG'S THREADS. THE PLUG WAS RESECURED AND TOOL TIGHTENED. PRODUCT MAY HAVE BEEN BY-PASSING THE CLOSED INTERNAL VALVING. AFTERWARDS, NATX 300257 WAS MONITORED AND SUBSEQUENT OBSERVATION REVEALED NO FURTHER PRODUCT DRIPS EVIDENT. TO REMEDIATE THE SMALL AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE, THE CONTRACTOR APPLIED MICRO BLAZE ATOP THE GROUND IMPACT AREA THAT WAS DIRECTLY UNDERNEATH THE BOV.

ON 3/31/06, SHIPPER OFF LOADED 2000 GALLONS OF LADING FROM GATX 44013 WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. GATX 44013 ALSO HAD A LIQUID RELEASE ONTHE BNSF IN MEMPHIS, TN ON 3/17/06.

column168: SPILL TOOK PLACE AT 9:15AM ON 3/31/2006 IN FORT MYERS FL.  THE LOCATION WAS AT FT. MYERS COLLISION 12490 METRO PARKWAY.  THE DRIVER MR. IANNACONE PARKED HIS TRUCK IN THE CENTER TURN LANE (BECAUSE COULD NOT GET HIS TRUCK IN TO CUSTOMERS PARKING LOT) HE WENT IN TO THE BODY SHOP AND REMOVED A 55 GALLON STEEL OPEN TOP DRUM OF WASTE PAINT MATERIAL.  THE DRIVER THEN TOOK IT BACK TO HIS TRUCK LOADED ON HIS LIFTGATE AND WENT TO MOVE THE DRUM INTO THE TRAILER.  THE DRUM SLIPPED OFF THE DRUM CART AND FELL TO THE FLOOR.  AT THIS TIME THE LID CAME OFF AND THE PAINT MATERIAL SPILLED INTO THE TRAILER AND ON TO THE ROADWAY.  MR IANNACONE WENT TO HIS SPILL KIT AND IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THE FIRE DEPT ARRIVED AND TOOK CONTROL OF THE SCENE.  THE FT MYERS HAZ-MAT AND DOT RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND USED SAND AND ABSORBANTS ON THE SPILL.  THE FIRE DEPT RELEASED THE SCENE TO CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR. CLEAN UP WAS THEN COMPLETED.
column169: TALKED TO MIKE IANNACONE ABOUT LOOKING AT ALL CONTAINERS THAT ARE FOR SHIPPMENT FOR LOOSE RINGS, LIDS, BOLTS, BUNGS ALSO LEAKS ECT.

column168: EMPLOYEE WENT TO LOAD CRUDE OIL WHEN HE REALIZED THAT HIS CRUDE PUMP WOULD NOT LOAD AND THERE WAS NO POWER TO THE TRAILERS INSTRUMENTATION.  AFTER CONSULTING WITH OUR MECHANICS, HE BEGAN TROUBLESHOOTING WHAT WAS WRONG AND MISTAKENLY LOOSENED THE HOSE COUPLING AT OUR TRAILERS MANIFOLD.  THE RESULT WAS THE RELEASE OF THE CONTENTS THE OF THE OIL IN HOSE ON GROUND WITH SOME GETTING ON HIM AS WELL AS THE TRANSPORT.
column169: ELECTRONICS WERE INADVERTENTLY SHORTED OUT ON THE TRAILER AFTER SECOND LOAD BY THE MECHANIC WORKING ON THE WORK LIGHTS.  NOT KNOWING THIS DRIVER ENGAGED HIS PTO WHILE LEAVING THE CAB THEN PROCEEDED TO WORK THE OIL.  AFTER FINDING OUT THE OIL WAS GOOD, HE OPENED UP THE TANK AND THEN OPENED THE TRAILER VALVE AND PUT THE CRUDE PUMP IN THE LOAD POSITION. NOTHING HAPPENED.  HE WAS SETTING THERE WITH THE HOSE FULL OF OIL. HE CALLED MECHANIC AND HE INSTRUCTED HIM TO CHECK THE TRAILER CORD CONNECTIONS AND BRAKE INTERLOCK, WHICH ALSO IS CONNECTED TO THE PUMP BYPASS WIRING.  KNOWING THAT BOTH THE TANK VALVE AND TRAILER VALVE WAS CLOSED; HE WAS GOING TO RELEASE THE EARS AND PUSH THE CONNECTION ON FURTHER TO ENSURE IT WAS DEPRESSED.  THE OIL HAD SAT IN THE HOSE FOR ABOUT 45 MINUTES PRIOR TO OPENING THE EARS ON THE HOSE AND MOST LIKELY WAS WARMED BY THE SUN.  WHEN HE OPENED THE EARS ON THE HOSE HE WAS NOT EXPECTING THE PRESSURE AND SPRAY. HE DROPPED THE HOSE TO GET OUT OF THE WAY.

column168: A loaded Union County Arkansas dump truck struck the side of the moving string of railcars (non-DOT Specification Hoppers) while crossing Hwy 7. It is unknown why the driver of the dump truck did not see the warning signals flashing at the railroad crossing and the train crossing Hwy 7; the dump truck did not appear to decrease highway speed when he struck the train. The impact caused the derailment of four hopper cars, all but one was loaded with ammonium nitrate fertilizer. Approximately 30 tons were spilled in the incident and one fatality. There were no avacuations, any other injuries, any direct environmental threat, but Hwy 7 was closed for approximately 36 hours.    Police and the fire department were called to the scene. Contractors immediately began to upright railcars, repair the railroad track and cantilever crossing devices and vacuum the pellets of ammonium nitrate. The impact of the dump truck striking the side of the hopper caused a three feet by three feet gash and forced open the top hatches and one gate of the car. The material was transported approximately four miles back to the point of origin, which was El Dorado Chemical Company.

column168: TRACTOR-TANKER TRANSPORTING LOAD OF NON-HAZARDOUS, NON-REGULATED RESIN INVOLVED IN SINGLE VEHICLE ROLL-OVER. NO RELEASE WAS EXPERIENCED DURING INCIDENT. UNIT WAS UP-RIGHTED AND TRANSPORTED TO SECURE LOCATION FOR TRANS LOAD TO SECOND UNIT.

VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING IN A NORTH DOWN A MODERATE TO STEEP INCLINE, APPROXIMATELY ON MILE LONG, AT 40 MPH.  WHEN ROUNDING A CURVE ABOUT 100 YARDS FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE HILL, AT THE STEEPEST INCLINE, I OBSERVED A TRUCK STOPPED.  IT WAS WAITING FOR ON COMING TRAFFIC BEFORE MAKING A LEFT TURN.  AS I APPLIED THE BRAKES HARDER TO COME TO A STOP I GOT NO RESPONSE.  PUMPING THE BRAKES GAVE NO RESPONSE.  I ATTEMPTED TO TURN LEFT ONTO SIDE ROAD IN ORDER TO PREVENT A REAR END COLLISION.  WHILE DOING SO THE STOPPED TRUCK BEGAN TO TURN AND THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE OF MY FUEL TRUCK RAN UPON A SMALL TOWED TRAILER.  IN DOING SO THE FUEL TRUCK TIPPED LEFT AND FELL OVER ON ITS SIDE.  WHEN VEHICLE STRUCK HIGHWAY PAVEMENT, THE FUEL TRUCK SEAM CRACKED AND RELEASE OCCURRED OVER 1.5 HOUR PERIOD OF TIME.  TOWNSHIP EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED SHORTLY AND LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRIVED WITHIN ½ HOUR.  THEY WERE WORKING NEARBY AND WERE ABLE TO COME IMMEDIATELY.  BEING THE DRIVER AND OWNER OF THE FUEL OIL COMPANY, AND TO MITIGATE DAMAGE, I HIRED THEM ON THE SPOT.  OIL BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE STREAM, ABSORBANTS TO LAYING FUEL OIL, AND PRODUCT REMOVED FROM TRUCK AND DITCH WORK CONTINUED THROUGH THE WEEKEND AND CONTINUED UNTIL ALL WORK WAS COMPLETED.
column169: I HAVE BEEN DELIVERING FUEL OIL FOR OVER 40 YEARS.  I HAVE DRIVEN THIS TRUCK FOR 11 YEARS.  IN ALL THAT TIME I NEVER HAD BRAKE PROBLEMS.  THEY WERE CHECKED AND NO PROBLEMS WERE FOUND.  MAYBE I SHOULD HAVE BEEN IN A LOWER GEAR TO SLOW DOWN AND RELIEVE THE HEAT ON THE BRAKES.  IT TURNED OUT TO BE DRIVER ERROR.

column168: TRANSPORTATION UNIT WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON COPUS ROAD. DRIVER SWITCHED HEADLIGHTS FROM LOW BEAM TO HIGH BEAM AND LOST ELECTRICAL POWER. WHEN DRIVER APPROACHED BASIC SCHOOL ROAD, THE TRANSPORTATION UNIT DRIFTED TO AND ENTERED THE NORTH SHOULDER OF COPUS ROAD. THE SHOULDER WAS A MIXTURE OF MUD AND SOIL. TRANSPORTATION DRIVER STEERED THE TRANSPORTATION UNIT TO THE LEFT IN AN ATTEMPT TO REENTER THE WESTBOUND LANE. THE TRAILER THEN SLID TO THE RIGHT AS THE UNIT CROSSED THE INTERSECTION OF BASIC SCHOOL ROAD. THE TRAILER IMPACTED WITH A HIGHWAY ADVISORY SIGN ON THE WEST SIDE SHOULDER OF BASIC SCHOOL ROAD. THE TRAILER THEN ROLLED ONTO IT SIDE STRIKING THREE STEEL POST, WHICH COMPROMISED THE TRAILER AND CAUSED THE RESULTING RELEASE OF CARGO.    UPON NOTIFICATION, FLYING J TRANSPORTATION, LLC IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE TEAM TO CONTAIN AND REMEDIATE THE RELEASE. DUE TO THE EXTENT OF CONTAMINATION, THE REMEDIATION EFFORTS CONTINUED UNTIL SEPTEMBER 2006. THE ALMOND GROVE IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE WAS RESTORED TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION, INCLUDING IMPACTED AREAS ALONG THE SHOULDERS OF COPUS ROAD AND BASIC SCHOOL ROAD. ALL ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS WERE SATISFIED AND THE SITE RECEIVED A “NO FUXTHER ACTION REQUIRED” STATUS BY THE KERN COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT.
column169: THE POWER UNIT INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WAS NEW, HAVING 11,000 MILES ON THE ODOMETER. FLYING J TRANSPORTATION CONDUCTED A POST ACCIDENT INVESTIGATION AND FOUND THAT JUST PRIOR TO THE INCIDENT, THE ONBOARD COMPUTER DETECTED A CATASTROPHIC POWER FAILURE (MECHANICAL) AFFECTING THE ENTIRE ELECTRICAL SYSTEM, WHICH SHUTDOWN THE ENGINE. DUE TO THE LOSS OF HEADLIGHTS, DASHBOARD LIGHTS AND THE ENGINE, THESE FAILURES ATTRIBUTED TO THE VEHICLE LOSING DIRECTION ON THE ROAD SURFACE. BECAUSE OF VEHICLE’S AGE AND LOW MILEAGE, FLYING J TRANSPORTATION CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURER TO RESOLVE THE MECHANICAL FAILURE. CURRENTLY, BOTH PARTIES HAVE ENTERED INTO LITIGATION RESOLVE THE MATTER. TRANSPORTATION DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO REVIEW ELECTRICAL DEFICIENCIES DURING THE PRE-TRIP INSPECTION. ALTHOUGH A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THIS VEHICLE DID NOT DETECT ANY DEFICIENCIES, DRIVERS WILL TAKE INTO CONSIDERATION THE POTENTIAL FOR SUCH DEFICIENCIES DURING THEIR INSPECTION. IF ANY ELECTRICAL FAILURE OCCURS, DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO IMMEDIATELY STOP THEIR VEHICLE AT THE SAFEST POSSIBLE POINT, AND NOT TO RESOLVE AN ELECTRICAL OR MECHANICAL PROBLEM WHEN THE VEHICLE IS IN MOTION.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN AN AUTOMOBILE MADE A U-TURN IN THE PATH OF PERRY OIL’S TANKER TRUCK, RESULTING IN A RELEASE OF 7,000 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL. THE DIESEL FUEL FLOWED OVER THE SIDE BANK OF THE HIGHWAY, FLOWED DOWN A CONCRETE FUME, AND ENTERED AN UNNAMED STREAM. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY, THEIR OFFICE BEING LESS THAN 1/4-MILE FROM THE INCIDENT LOCATION. BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE STREAM, ALLOWING MAXIMIZATION OF FREE PRODUCT RECOVERY EFFORTS VIA SKIMMING WITH A VAC TRUCK. IMPACTS WERE MOSTLY RESTRICTED TO THE STREAM. OBVIOUSLY IMPACTED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED AND SHIELD TESTED SOILS WITHIN APPARENTLY AFFECTED AREAS. STREAM WATER SAMPLES INDICATED NON-DETECTABLE CONCENTRATIONS OF POLYNUCLEAR AROMATIC HYDROCARBONS (PAH). THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREWS PERFORMED DAILY, AND THEN WEEKLY MAINTENANCE OF ABSORBENT BOOMS AND PADS OVER THE SEVERAL WEEKS UNTIL SHEEN WAS NO LONGER OBSERVED. A PHOTOGRAPH OF THE TRUCK FAILURE IS ATTACHED.
column169: CONSIDERING THAT WE HAVE RESPONDED WITHIN 45 DAYS OF RECEIPT OF YOUR LETTER, WE REQUEST THAT THE MATTER BE CLOSED. THE KENTUCKY REGULATORY AGENCIES HAVE ALREADY CLOSED THE INCIDENT AND THE REPORTS WERE FILED WITH THE FEDERAL EPA (REGION IV). SINCE THE ACCIDENT WAS THE FAULT OF THE OTHER DRIVER, AND NOT PERRY OIL PERSONNEL, PERRY OIL INTENDS TO RESPOND BY CONTINUING TO EDUCATE AND RAISE THE AWARENESS OF OUR FLEET DRIVERS OF THE POTENTIAL FOR ACCIDENTS AND SUGGEST WAYS TO AVOID SUCH ACCIDENTS.

column168: Driver heard a noise come from the trailer.  Stopped off the side of the roadway.  Got out to investigate.  Found a stream of liquid coming from the rear of his trailer.  In an attempt to stop the leakage, the driver used his shirt to put in the cracks at the rear trailer door, prior to calling the safety department.  2 fire trucks, DOT officer: Ofc. Mallahan, 2 local police, 2 Highway patrol, 1 Chief of Fire Department:  Casey (JE) Wright with the Manchester Fire Department. LERC Chad Pardin at the scene.  NRC contacted today, after discovering injuries.  Report #791432, Ms. Johnson.  This was an un-caged tote, nothing to secure it from outside punctures.  Highway patrol went to hospital because some of the liquid was discovered on the bottom of her shoes.  The driver was checked out and released same night with minor chemical burns, that as of today appear to have healed very well.  MSDS was faxed to all agencies involved.  It is understood after investigation the strap let loose while in transit allowing the tote to roam free in the trailer as it was the only object left to deliver.  The tote made it's way to the rear of the trailer where it received a puncture hole, had a cage been surrounding tote, this probably would not have happened.  Our event #36661.
column169: Do not accept any un-caged or un-protected totes from shippers.  Double check straps to assure they are in good working order prior to use (daily).  Use multiple straps in case was fails, other straps will keep product secure.

column168: Description of Incident:    On March 10th 2006, Troy Thompson was hooking Rail car GATX42580 containing CCA, a Chromated Copper Arsenate liquid to off load the product to the storage tank.  Mr. Thompson hooked up hose to the on site transfer pipe and hooked up the hose to rail car at 13:15HR and turned on the pump to begin the transfer.  Our Liquids Lead operator Dennis Morgan noticed product was released on the sides of rail car and on the ground.  There is no containment for railcar unloading facility.  The spill response contractor was called upon at 13:30HR and they were on the site to begin recovery of the contaminated soil and to clean the sides of railcar.  Mr. Thompson was tested for drugs and the results were negative.    The results of Investigation:    The liquid foreman determined that there was no gasket in the transfer hose.  Mr. Thompson made statement that he agreed that there was no gasket at the connection and he made a mistake.  He assumed that the gasket was there.  The gasket was found to be with the cap at the later time.  Mr. Thompson has been employed since April 2000 and has been an excellent operator.  At the time of the incident he was working along with more experienced Liquids Foreman Mr. Dennis Morgan as part of the terminals reorientation process for employees who have not worked recently in the liquid yard.    The site was cordoned off the rinse water were collected in separate totes and dir was removed.  All the soil and rinse water are analyzed by a certified laboratory.  Our consulting engineering group is working with State agency to assure that proper care is taken to remove the contaminated soil and waste water and soil are disposed of manner that meets all the local and other regulatory requirements
column169: Recommendation to Prevent Recurrence:    * Initiate a project to provide containment for this product at the rail off lading facility.    *  Consider discontinuing the storage and handling of CCA.  If the decision is made to continue handling the product., adequate containment must be installed.    *  It was not determined if the camlock fitting has been shimmed to compensate for a worn out gasket.  There should be no reason to shim equipment used in CCA transfers-if the camlock unit is not working properly it should be repaired or replaced.    Corrective/Investigative Actions:    Action by Tony Habersetzer, Terminal Manager: Take appropriate retraining/discipline action in regards to operator Thompson, Due date 31, March 2006.    Action by Tony Habersetzer:  Prepare written procedures for CCA rail transfer operations,  Emphasize that shim is not to be used for CCA or other noxious chemical transfers.  Consider use of new gasket for every transfer, Due Date 31 March 2006.    Action Rich Arrasmith: Senior Area Manager:  Review the CCA contract with the customer.  Determine if CCA should be discontinued, or if it is more appropriate to make the investment for proper CCA transfer facilities.  Due date: 31 March 2006.    Action Tony Habersetzer:  Discuss this incident at the next safety meeting from a lesson learned perspective.  Ensure that terminal training program emphasizes the importance of ensuring transfer hose gaskets are in place and in serviceable condition.  Emphasize each employee is taking time to each job is done correctly.  Due date: 31 March 2006.

column168: On March 9, 2006 at approx. 12:45 p.m., Mike Mecham was driving a tanker truck and trailer northbound on SH 28 at MP120. Driver rounded a left hand curve and entered into a straight a way. As the roadway straightened, Mecham drifted off of the right side of the roadway and into a gravel barrow pit. As driver swerved the truck back onto the pavement, the trailer began to swerve back and forth, which ultimately broke connection from the truck. The trailer crossed left of center and went into the southbound barrow pit where it rolled in a corkscrew manuever. The trailer rolled 3/4 of a revolution and came to rest on it's right side. Approximately 600 gallons of fuel leaked from the trailers dome lids into the ground. Dome clamps were applied to slow the leakage until clean up crews arrived.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THE BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING.  UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND A BATTERY WRAPPED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND LYING ON IT'S SIDE.  THE PLASTIC BAG WAS NOT SEALED.  THE BOX IS ALSO SUPPOSED TO HAVE END CAPS TO PREVENT THE BATTERY FROM TIPPING OVER, THE END CAPS WERE MISSING.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA KATE ZAMPARELLI IN BOS.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

The box was found leaking. The material that spilled was a non-aerosol bottle of WD-40 but there were 3 other undeclared hazardous substances in the box. They are:  one l25ml can of GOOF OFF brand adhesive remover (main ingredient is Xylene), one ll8ml tube of Liquid Nails brand small projects and repairs interior adhesive (contains several highly flammable chemicals), and one 177ml bottle of nail polish remover (main ingredient is Acetone). There were no markings, labeling, shipping papers, emergency response information nor other indicators to lead us to believe the contents were regulated. The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Bryan Buchanan. The freight was held pending an FAA inspection.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: PACKAGE WAS PUSHED DOWN THE SLIDE AND TUMBLED UPSIDE DOWN. IT THEN VENTED VISIBLE GAS LIKE THAT OF DRY ICE, WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED RIGHT SIDE UP, LIQUID SPILLED OUT QUICKLY TURNING INTO GAS UPON GROUND CONTACT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE, NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAZ WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA MARK GENTILE. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

THE BOX WAS FOUND LEAKING AND GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR. THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL BUBBLEWRAP AND BROKEN GLASS. AS THE SHIPPER IS KNOWN FOR SHIPPING PERFUME WE NOTIFIED THEM AND ASKED HOW MANY INNER BOTTLES WERE OFFERED. THE RESPONSE I RECEIVED FROM BOB KROIS, THE INDIVIDUAL WHO SIGNED THE SHIPPING PAPER, WAS THAT THERE WAS ONLY ONE INNER AND THAT IT MAY HAVE EXCEEDED THE 500 ML LIMIT. BASED ON THE FACT THAT THIS PACKAGE SPILLED, THERE WAS NO ABSORBANT MATERIAL & THE BELIEF THAT THE INNER BOTTLE EXCEEDED THE QUANTITY LIMIT, THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. I SPOKE TO SAS JOE BALLAS & JOE CLARK FROM EWR. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING. THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL FOUR BOTTLES WITH DIFFERENT COMMODITIES IN EACH. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ULTIMATELY WE WERE ADVISED THAT THE MSDS COULD BE OBTAINED THROUGH THE GRAINGER WEBSITE. MSDS WERE PRINTED OFF THE WEBSITE AND WE FOUND THAT PRODUCT CODE 3ZA76, COFFEE & TANNIN STAIN REMOVER WAS A PG III, CLASS 3. EVEN THOUGH THE PRODUCT DID NOT LEAK, IT WAS UNDECLARED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA KATE ZAMPARELLI IN BOS. THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

TRIS FEDEX BOX CAME OPEN DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AND 19 BOXES OF SPARKLERS  WERE FOUND INSIDE THIS PACKAGE. EACH OF THESE INNER BOXES CONTAINED 6 SPARKLERS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND SEA FAA AGENT JOE DEROCHE WAS CONTACTED AND WAS TO  INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND WAS ADVISED OF THIS  SHIPPING ERROR. HE WAS TO FOLLOW-UP WITH HIS EMPLOYEES

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: On 03/10/06 at 1835 hrs, Trainmaster Bill Kelly reported to the CSXT PCC, tank car GATX 5919 was releasing product ( sulfuric acid) from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and environmental contractor, Eagle Construction, was called to respond to the leak, Chemtrec was notified of the spill, report #03 102006087. Eagle Construction inspected the car and found the 165 lb. rupture disc was blown. The rupture disc was replaced, the car was decontaminated and soda ash was applied to the ground where the acid was spilled. The car was released to destination.        Cause Code:: 441  NARRI: 2(5+5+0) x (2+0) =40

column168: RESIDUE SHIPMENT IN TANK CAR UTLX 950829 WAS NOTED BY FRA HAZMAT INPECTOR MATSINGER WITH A HISSING NOISE COMING FROM THE (B) END LIQUIED LINE.    INVESTIGATION BY SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVES REVEALED A DEFECTIVE LIQUIED LINE VALVE AND LOOSE CAP ALLOWING PRODUCT VAPOR TO ESCAPE.    THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE.  THE CAR WILL MOVE UNDER FRA MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO A CERTIFIED REPAIR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

ON 03/17/2006, 11:30 HRS CSX HAZ-MAT RECEIVED A CALL REPORTING CAR PROX 55025 TO HAVE A SLOSH LEAK FOMR THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED INT EH CUMBERLAND YARD OF CSX.  CSX HAZ-MAT DISPATCHED SPECIALIZED PREFESSIONAL SERVICES (SPSI) DRE MCCARTY 877-228-7774 TO INSPECT THE CAR.  CSX HAZ-MAT NOTIFIED SHIPER VIA CHEMTREC, REPORT #03172006035.  SPSI FOUND A 3" LIQIUD EDUCTION LINE (NO VLAVE), WITH THE CPA WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND NO GASKET IN THE CPA.  THE SHIPPER INDICATED THAT A GASEKT WAS NOT NECESSARY-IT WAS A PIPE TO PIPE FITTING.  PRESSURE WAS RELEAVED OFF THE CAR AND THE CAP TIGHTENED TO TOOL TIGHT.  NO FURTHER PRODUCT WAS RELASED FROM ACAR.  THE SIDES OF THE CAR WERE WIPED DOWN AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED WITH NO FURTHER DEFECTS.

On Thursday March 16, 2006, UTLX 630162 derailed from tracks in Suffolk, VA. This was a loaded tank car of Sodium Hydroxide that did not leak. The Fire Department ordered an evacuation of a single family home (7 people) due to the close proximity of the house to the derailed car. The family was brought to the local Fire  Department as a precaution. Hepaco Environmental was dispatched to standby durning rerailing operations. The car was rerailed without incident and the evacuation was lifted 1340 hrs.  Chemtrec Report #0316200612

column168: During the PM sort, this shipment was discovered to contain various chemicals. MSDS information reveals that two of the chemcials appear to be regulated dangerous goods. The shipment was not marked, labeled or documented to contain dangerous goods. The shipment was held pending FAA investigation. Agent Greg Porter, FAA, PHL was notified on 2/29/06 at 2:30 PM CST.

At 10:30am I received a call from Dick Hester informing me that we had a possible leaking tank car in Joliet Yard as a crew handling the subject car had smelled an odor while handling it. Upon my arrival at Joliet Yard, I walked out to the south end of North-6 where the car was located and noticed that indeed the subject car (GATX with a load of Hexene which is a Class 3 Flammable Liquid UN 2370) was leaking from the valves on top of the tank car at a rate of one drop every four to five seconds (it was now 12:23pm). I contacted S.0. Benaviades at 12:30pm and asked him to have the tracks locked out.  Hal Ratton from Equistar (who had been called earlier) arrived at the scene with his hazardous response team at 12:50pm and verified the leak at 1:11pm after the car inspector had the track locked out.  He then had a job briefing with his team near the South End Yard Office and then went back out into the yard with his team at 1:45pm to start repairs on the subject car. At 2:05pm he informed me that all repairs had been made and that the car was OK to move.  He stated that the cause of the leak was loose plugs on a sample valve. Joliet yard operations sustained a delay from 10:30am until 2:05pm as a result of this incident.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS, STABILIZED WITH MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE
column168: At 2120 hours, on 31 March 2006, at Leewood Yard, Memphis, TN, a car inspector reported a small fire under TELX 17018, load, Hydrogen Peroxide, Aqueous Solution, UN2015, in the gauge of the tracks. TELX 17018 was on the inbound interchange track from the CN Railway that arrived at 2015 hours. The car inspector reported the incident to the Yardmaster. The (TERP) Transportation Emergency Response Plan was implemented, the CSXT Hazardous Material System Call Duty Officer was advised and the Local Fire Department was called to respond. CHEMTREC was notified Report #03312006-106, and was requested to contact the shipper ARKEMA, Inc. of Memphis, TN. An Emergency Response Contractor, HEPACO of Memphis, TN, responded to inspect Tank Car TELX 17018. ARKEMA, Inc. also responded with an ER Team. HEPACO and ARKEMA found the Rupture Disc, (“stone” type) had cracked. Approximately 2 gallons of product was released from TELX 17018 and cleaned up. The rupture disc was replaced and the car was released for disposition.

column168: Tankcar GATX 89113 was reported releasing product from top of car at Dallas Street Yard MP 1297.53 El Paso Texas. Mr. John Jackson, Manager Chemical Transportation Safety was notified and responded. Mr. Jackson discovered product had been released due to a loose liquid line valve plug and partially open liquid line valve. Mr. Jackson secured the open valve and tightened the plug tool tight, stopping the release. Viva Environmental was notified and responded to clean the residue from the top and sides of the car. Mr. Jackson inspected the car and released to destination with no other exceptions. Shipper was notified via Chemtrec.

column42: ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL OR ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, WITH MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: Harry, RTS Gate Supervisor, Seattle, WA. reported a release of hazardous material from Container MOFU 047524 at Pad 290 of the Seattle Hump Yard in Seattle, WA. Vern Libby, Senior Special Agent Hazmat, was notified and responded. Libby advised thre was a minor leak with an unknown quantity and it was not close to any waterways. Agent Libby stated remediation company NRC Environmental was responding to remediate. All state notifications were made. Libby advised NRC Environmental had arrived on scene, and the container was relocated to a plastic sheet on the ground. At 07:44 PM, Libby advised thirty gallons of acetic acid glacial had been released within the container, with one 9allon released onto the ground due to a nail punctured drum. Passenger John Friend reported that his baggage was contaminated with a flammable liquid and contacted the Southwest Airlines Baggage Service office at ISP to report the damage upon arrival into ISP. It is assumed that the fuel involved is either lighter fluid, Jet A or kerosene based on feedback from witness accounts.  It is still undetermined what the source of the flammable liquid online his baggage is from. Local Airport Police, Fire Department personnel and the local HAZMAT Team responded to the bag, moved and containerized the materials that were saturated. The teams worked with Southwest Airlines to inspect the field, aircraft arid equipment for further contamination.    No additional contamination was discovered at ISP, on the aircraft nor in or on other Customer baggage. Orlando (MCO) was contacted to determine if there had been a fuel spill and both the local Fire Department and Southwest Airlines confirmed that there was no spill.    At this point we suspect that an undeclared material may have been the cause of the incident, but have been unable to track down the source.

column168: Tank Car GATX 10964 was reported leaking Sodium Hydroxide when delivered to Consignee BHS in Nampa Idaho on March 16, 2006. The estimated amount of the release was 20 gallons and was contained to the sides and top of the car. The cause of the release was a blown rupture disk. The rupture disk was replaced by BHS personnel. The car was pressure washed and cleaned returning the car to service. Per 49CFR 171.16 (a) Each person in physical control of a hazardous material at the time that there is an unintentional release of a hazardous material must submit a Hazardous Material incident report on DOT Form 5800.1. Release was discovered by BHS personnel while the tank car was in their control, therefore; they are responsible for the DOT 5800.1 report. Union Pacific is submitting this report as information only.

On March 29th at approximately 1311 hours, I was contacted by the Colorado State Patrol’s Communication Center advising of a reported hazardous materials release located at the westbound Dumont, Colorado Ports of Entry (1-70 Ml? 234) located in the county of Clear Creek, State of Colorado. 1 responded along with my partner Technician Doug Barnes and arrived to the location at approximately 1344 hours. While in route, we requested through our communication center that the trucking company seek another vehicle for offloading and a clean up contractor to be made available and on standby. Too, we requested additional H.AZMAT Technicians from Summit County, as no other Colorado State Patrol HAZMAT Technicians were available. Upon arrival, I observed a tractor/DOT 412-tank type vehicle, parked on the Port property, near the Port office. I was unable to view any material leak from our position. Prior to our arrival, the Port office had been evacuated, a protection perimeter put in place and secured. Next, I was approached by Brian Cales, and identified himself to me as the driver of the vehicle. He informed me that the product was a 28% solution of Hydrochloric Acid and the vehicle had lost approximately two quarts of product. We re-positioned ourselves to a closer vantage point to observe the vehicle. We moved upwind and west of the vehicle; approximately 200 feet away from the vehicle, from there, I was able to observe the tank and its leak. It appeared the leak was coining from the rear and bottom of the tank, near the valving area. It appeared that the container had lost approximately five gallons at the time. Barnes and I consulted our resource materials for known hazards and reactivity with other substances we could possibly use to contain the substance. The nature of the product required that entry be made in level B protection (with SCBA). We also requested a load of sand material from CDOT be on standby and available to cover the product (NIOSH/ ERG) if needed. I coordinated with Barnes and it was decided that we would make an initial assessment entry, once a decontamination area and supporting technicians were set up and on location. Once in place, we made entry at approximately 1521 hours along with Sgt. A. Driscoll. During entry, we brought a plugging kit, wrenches, and a containment pool in hopes of stopping the leak.
